# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andrew-linzey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andrew-linzey/a-breeze-harper] Harper attributes her initial interest in practicing veganism to the influence of the work of Dick Gregory in connecting diet to the liberation struggle of marginalized groups, and to Afrocentric, raw foodist Queen Afua.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-breeze-harper] In 2015, Harper organized a conference, *The Vegan Praxis of Black Lives Matters*, to discuss intersectional issues concerning veganism and the Black Lives Matter movement.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-breeze-harper] In the same year, Harper joined the advisory board for *Black Vegans Rock*.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-breeze-harper] Harper was the Humane Party's vice-presidential nominee for the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] In 1893, Cole prepared a set of vegetarian menus that received high commendation at the Universal Cookery Exhibition.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] The menus were later published as "Menus for a Week in November" in Rachel Swain's *Swain Cookery* and in Florence I.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] Nicholson's *The Jubilee Cookery Book: Vegetarian Recipes*.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] Cole worked in several London vegetarian organisations.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] Tovey in founding the Battersea, Clapham and Wandsworth Vegetarian Society, with A.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] She was a committee member of the Women's Vegetarian Union and gave a cookery lesson for the union at the offices of the Vegetarian Federal Union in 1898.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] According to James Gregory, Cole worked as an assistant to Nicholson and later to Charlotte Despard.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] She succeeded Nicholson as editor of *The Children's Realm*.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] By 1914, she was honorary secretary of the Vegetarian Federal Union.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] Cole gave public talks and demonstrations on vegetarian cookery.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] In 1910, as secretary of the West London Vegetarian Society, she gave a cookery demonstration at a vegetarian dinner held by the society at Pirbright Hall, Southfields.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] In 1913, as honorary secretary of the London Vegetarian Society, she spoke on "What is Vegetarianism" at a meeting at the Adult School in Sutton.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] In July 1915, *The Jewish Chronicle* published an interview with Cole, then secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, on vegetarianism and Jewish dietary practice.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] She argued that a vegetarian diet was compatible with Jewish religious observance and discussed food economy during the First World War.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] In 1917, when described as a former organising secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, she gave cookery demonstrations for the Food and Cookery Association in Southampton, where she presented vegetarian menus and methods for reducing food waste.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] Cole was listed as secretary of the Children's Dinner Fund in 1916.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] Hilda Kean writes that Nicholson established the fund for underfed children, distributing cheap meals of vegetable soup, wholemeal bread, and wholemeal currant bread.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-m-cole] In 1921, Cole was honorary secretary and organiser of the Women's Freedom League Settlement in Nine Elms, which provided daily penny and halfpenny hot meals for more than 100 children and operated a milk depot.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:andrew-linzey/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:andrew-linzey/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] Linzey is the founder and director of the Oxford Centre for Animal Ethics, an independent academic centre opened in November 2006 for the study and discussion of animal ethics.
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] His books on animals and theology include *Animal Rights: A Christian Perspective* (1976), *Christianity and the Rights of Animals* (1987), *Animal Theology* (1994), and *Why Animal Suffering Matters: Philosophy, Theology, and Practical Ethics* (2009).
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] He is co-editor, with his daughter Clair Linzey, of the *Journal of Animal Ethics*, and a series editor with Clair, previously with Priscilla Cohn, of the Palgrave Macmillan Animal Ethics Series.
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] Linzey has authored or edited 30 books and published more than 100 articles.
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] He has lectured and broadcast in Europe and the United States.
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] His writings have appeared in translation in several languages, including Italian, French, Polish, Spanish, German, Chinese, Taiwanese, and Japanese.
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] He has criticised Christian attitudes to animals, saying that "Christians haven't got much further than thinking that the whole world was made for us, with the result that animals are only seen in an instrumental way as objects, machines, tools, and commodities, rather than fellow creatures".
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] In 2012, *Christian Today* reported that Linzey had called for people convicted of animal cruelty to be placed on a register and barred from keeping or working with animals.
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] In 1990, Linzey was awarded the Peaceable Kingdom Medal for his work in theology and animals.
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] In June 2001, George Carey, Archbishop of Canterbury, awarded him a Doctor of Divinity degree in recognition of his "unique and massive pioneering work in the area of the theology of creation with particular reference to the rights and welfare of God's sentient creatures".
[src:andrew-linzey/andrew-linzey] In 2006, after the creation of the Oxford Centre for Animal Ethics, Linzey was named the Henry Bergh Professor of Animal Ethics at the Graduate Theological Foundation in the United States.
